Some smallholder farmers in Osun State have received from the Federal Government farm inputs and seedlings as part of efforts to improve their capacity and create investment in the agric sector. Speaking at the event where the items were distributed in Osogbo, the Minister for Agriculture, Muhammad Abubakar, represented by the Permanent Secretary of the ministry, Dr Ernest Umakhihe, said the distribution would stimulate investment, create jobs and facilitate increase in food production. Abubakar said the items were given to farmers free, adding that 35 per cent of the items were given to women farmers. He said, “having carefully assessed the negative impacts of COVID-19 pandemic, my ministry designed a support programmes targeting smallholder farmers to enhance the farming family income, create jobs and generate wealth. “The agricultural sector has been a priority for the current administration which becomes necessary to stimulate local production of food to achieve self-sufficiency, attract investments, create jobs and enhance the livelihood of farming families. “The sector has become one of the major contributors to the country’s economy, contributing about 25 per cent to our GDP, while smallholder farmers account for about 70 per cent of national food production. “This was achieved through the implementation of strategic policies such as the Agriculture for Food and Jobs Plan, the Green Imperative, Agricultural Promotion Policy as well as the Presidential Fertiliser Initiative, among others.” Copyright PUNCH. All rights reserved. This material, and other digital content on this website, may not be reproduced, published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed in whole or in part without prior express written permission from PUNCH. Contact: theeditor@punchng.com